        "title": "See also"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The Blackman window is defined as"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "formulas": [
              "w(n) = 0.42 - 0.5 \\cos(2\\pi n/M) + 0.08 \\cos(4\\pi n/M)"
            ],
            "type": "math_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Most references to the Blackman window come from the signal processing\nliterature, where it is used as one of many windowing functions for\nsmoothing values.  It is also known as an apodization (which means\n\"removing the foot\", i.e. smoothing discontinuities at the beginning\nand end of the sampled signal) or tapering function. It is known as a\n\"near optimal\" tapering function, almost as good (by some measures)\nas the kaiser window."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Notes"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Blackman, R.B. and Tukey, J.W., (1958) The measurement of power spectra,\nDover Publications, New York."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "Oppenheim, A.V., and R.W. Schafer. Discrete-Time Signal Processing.\nUpper Saddle River, NJ: Prentice-Hall, 1999, pp. 468-471."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "References"
      },
